HOW TO LAUNCH CLAUDE CODE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Open Terminal (Mac) or Command Prompt (Windows)
2. Navigate to your project folder:
   Mac:     cd ~/Desktop/risk-intelligence-index
   Windows: cd %USERPROFILE%\Desktop\risk-intelligence-index
3. Type: claude
4. Press Enter
5. Paste the entire brief below as your first message


================================================================================
OPENING BRIEF — PASTE THIS INTO CLAUDE CODE
================================================================================

I have an HTML file called index.html in this folder. It is a Risk Intelligence
Index dashboard. Please read it thoroughly before doing anything else.

Once you have read it, I need you to build a complete backend server and deploy
the entire project so it is live on the web. Here is exactly what needs to be
built:


BACKEND REQUIREMENTS:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Build a Node.js Express backend server. The HTML file already has a variable
called PROXY_BASE_URL at the top — once the backend is running, this variable
should point to the backend's URL so live data flows into the dashboard
automatically.

The backend needs to fetch data from the following sources and serve it to the
HTML file:

1. POLYMARKET
Fetch from the Polymarket CLOB API (clob.polymarket.com) and Gamma API
(gamma-api.polymarket.com). Fetch all active markets in these categories:
politics, world, middle-east, russia-ukraine, nato, china, economics, crypto,
stocks, fed, commodities, technology, ai, law, health, science.
Filter to markets with at least $10,000 in 24-hour volume.
Refresh prices every 30 seconds.
Fetch metadata once on load and cache it.
Fetch historical daily prices on demand when a market ID is requested.
No API key required.

2. KALSHI
Fetch from the Kalshi REST API. Requires a free API key which I will provide.
Fetch all open markets in these categories: geopolitics, foreign-policy,
middle-east, russia, china, nato, politics, congress, president, supreme-court,
elections, economics, fed, stocks, commodities, crypto, inflation, technology,
ai, cybersecurity, legal, regulation, security, health, disease, fda.
Filter to markets with at least $10,000 in 24-hour volume.
Flatten all series into individual markets.
Refresh every 30 seconds.
Fetch history on demand.

3. FRED + VIX LIVE UPDATES
Fetch from the FRED API at api.stlouisfed.org. Requires a free API key which
I will provide. Fetch these series:
  VIXCLS            — VIX Volatility Index (daily close fallback)
  SP500             — S&P 500
  DGS10             — 10-Year Treasury Yield
  FEDFUNDS          — Federal Funds Rate
  CPIAUCSL          — US Inflation (CPI)
  UNRATE            — Unemployment Rate
  A191RL1Q225SBEA   — US GDP Growth
  RECPROUSM156N     — US Recession Probability
Refresh FRED daily at 6pm ET.
Use the FRED release calendar endpoint to time monthly data releases precisely.
Serve full history on demand.

VIX INTRADAY — in addition to FRED daily close:
Fetch intraday VIX data from the Yahoo Finance API (symbol: ^VIX) every 5
minutes during US market hours (9:30am-4:00pm ET, Monday-Friday).
Outside market hours and on weekends, use the most recent FRED VIXCLS daily
close value as the displayed figure.
Store both intraday and daily values in the fred_data table.
The GET /api/fred endpoint must return a vix object with these fields:
  value       — current VIX number
  source      — "intraday" or "daily-close"
  market_open — true/false indicating whether US markets are currently open
  updated_at  — timestamp of last successful fetch
This allows the dashboard to display a "Live" indicator next to the VIX during
market hours and a "Close" indicator outside market hours.

4. GJOPEN
Scrape gjopen.com once daily.
Extract all active question titles, current community probability estimates,
number of forecasters, close dates, and recent probability history.
Map questions to these categories: geo, uspol, fin, tech, cyber, legal,
safety, medical.

5. RSS NEWS
Fetch and parse the following RSS feeds:

Breaking news — refresh every 5 minutes:
  feeds.reuters.com/reuters/topNews
  feeds.reuters.com/Reuters/PoliticsNews
  feeds.reuters.com/reuters/businessNews
  apnews.com/rss/apf-topnews
  feeds.bbci.co.uk/news/world/rss.xml
