           S&P, markets, stocks, bonds, crypto, Bitcoin
  tech:    AI, artificial intelligence, tech, Silicon Valley, OpenAI, Nvidia,
           semiconductor, regulation, data
  cyber:   hack, breach, ransomware, cyberattack, malware, vulnerability,
           NSA, CISA, infrastructure attack
  legal:   court, ruling, lawsuit, antitrust, DOJ, SEC, FTC, verdict,
           indictment, regulation, enforcement
  safety:  terrorism, attack, shooting, explosion, threat, extremism, nuclear,
           chemical weapon, bioterrorism
  medical: outbreak, pandemic, virus, WHO, FDA, vaccine, disease, public
           health, CDC, epidemic, variant

6. AI PLATFORMS CONSENSUS
Pre-compute AI Platforms Consensus probability estimates for every active
market and non-monied signal once daily at 2:00am ET.

For each market and signal, call the Claude API (claude-sonnet-4-20250514)
with the following standardized prompt, replacing the bracketed fields:

  "You are simulating how different AI platforms would independently assess
  a risk signal's probability. Signal: [market name]. Category: [cat].
  Current market/survey value: [prob]%. Date: [today].
  Give realistic probability estimates that each major AI platform would
  plausibly give, reflecting their known tendencies:
  Claude: nuanced/cautious;
  GPT-4o: slightly optimistic;
  Gemini: data-driven/moderate;
  Grok: contrarian/bold;
  DeepSeek: quantitative/analytical;
  Mistral: conservative/European-policy-aware;
  Perplexity: search-grounded/news-anchored.
  Estimates should reflect genuine variation — avoid clustering all models
  within 2-3pp of each other.
  Reply ONLY with valid JSON, no markdown fences:
  {models:[
    {id:'claude',pct:NUMBER},
    {id:'deepseek',pct:NUMBER},
    {id:'gemini',pct:NUMBER},
    {id:'gpt4',pct:NUMBER},
    {id:'grok',pct:NUMBER},
    {id:'mistral',pct:NUMBER},
    {id:'perplexity',pct:NUMBER}
  ],consensus_note:'one sentence max 15 words on where models agree or diverge'}"

Store all results in a database table called ai_consensus with fields:
  market_id       — the market or signal ID
  claude_pct      — Claude probability estimate
  deepseek_pct    — DeepSeek probability estimate
  gemini_pct      — Gemini probability estimate
  gpt4_pct        — GPT-4o probability estimate
  grok_pct        — Grok probability estimate
  mistral_pct     — Mistral probability estimate
  perplexity_pct  — Perplexity probability estimate
  avg_pct         — rounded average across all seven models
  spread          — difference between highest and lowest estimate
  consensus_note  — the one-sentence summary from the model
  computed_at     — timestamp of when this was computed

Add a new API endpoint:
  GET /api/consensus/:id
  Returns the pre-computed consensus object for a given market or signal ID.
  If no pre-computed result exists for an ID, fall back to a live Claude API
  call using the same prompt above.

Update index.html so the _spFetchConsensus function checks
GET /api/consensus/:id first before making a live API call. This eliminates
per-user API calls and makes the consensus section load instantly for users.

The AI consensus daily job should process markets in batches of 20 to avoid
rate limiting. Log any failures and retry failed markets in the next run.
Estimated daily API cost for this job: $0.50-$1.00 at current Claude pricing
for approximately 150-210 active markets and signals.

NOTE ON FUTURE AI MODEL UPGRADES:
The ai_consensus table and prompt are designed so that real API calls to
OpenAI (GPT-4o), Google (Gemini), Mistral, DeepSeek, and Perplexity can
replace Claude's simulated estimates for those models in a later phase,
one model at a time, without changing the database schema or frontend.
When real API keys for those models are provided, update the daily job to
call each model's API directly for its own estimate.


7. ENTERPRISE PULSE SURVEY
The dashboard includes an Enterprise Pulse Survey feature that generates
short internal survey questions for teams to pressure-test their awareness
of specific risk signals. Users open it from either a specific signal in
the index ("Pulse Survey" button on a signal card) or via the standalone
"Build a Custom Survey" entry point.

There are two generation flows, both currently implemented as direct calls
from index.html to the Anthropic API. Both must be proxied through the
backend so the Anthropic API key is never exposed to the browser.

Flow A — Single-topic (called from a specific signal card):
  Input:  signal name, category ID, current probability (if available),
          industry label derived from category
  Output: exactly 5 questions — 2 Likert (1-5), 2 Yes/No, 1 open-ended —
          plus a one-sentence industry_context string
  Prompt intent: plain-language, no jargon, questions built literally
  around the topic; no "CRO lens", no "leadership vs frontline gap"
  framing, no compound questions; questions ask what a working
  professional would know or have an opinion on (awareness, expectations,
  likelihood, concern level, organizational impact)

Flow B — Custom multi-topic builder:
  Input:  survey name, list of selected topics (signal + category),
          optional sector calibration
  Output: between 2 and 10 questions (scales with topic count, capped at
          10), covering every selected topic at least once; mix of scale /
          yes-no / open; plus a survey_title and one-sentence summary
  Prompt intent: same plain-language constraints as Flow A

Both prompts reply in strict JSON. JSON schemas are embedded in the
existing index.html — the backend must preserve those exact field names:
  questions:    [{num, text, type, low?, high?, placeholder?, topic?}]
  industry_context | summary | survey_title

Add these endpoints:
  POST /api/pulse/generate-single
    Body: {signal_name, category, probability, industry_label}
    Returns: {questions, industry_context}

  POST /api/pulse/generate-custom
    Body: {survey_name, topics:[{sig, cat}], sector}
    Returns: {survey_title, questions, summary}

Editable questions UI (frontend-only, no backend changes needed):
After generation, users can edit each question's text, change its response
type (scale / yes-no / open), edit low/high scale labels or open-response
placeholder, delete questions, and add their own blank questions via a
"+ Add your own question" button. Question numbers renumber automatically.
The backend only needs to produce the initial array — the frontend mutates
it in memory before send.

Delivery (Phase 2 of this feature — post-launch):
The survey modal has a "Deliver" tab listing Slack, Microsoft Teams,
Google Chat, Email, and Microsoft Forms. At launch these are presented as
"Connect in settings to enable" placeholders. Post-launch, add:
  POST /api/pulse/send
    Body: {survey_title, questions, platforms:[...], settings:{anonymous,
          expires_at, etc.}, recipients}
  And per-platform OAuth integrations for Slack, Teams, Google Workspace,
  and SMTP-based email delivery.

Cost estimate: each survey generation ~$0.005-$0.010 in Claude API costs.
Assume <100 surveys/day at launch — negligible daily cost.


8. SIDE-PANEL SIGNAL BRIEFINGS
When a user clicks any market or signal card in the index, a side panel
opens showing a generated briefing: a 7-point trend sparkline, 3 driver
bullets (title + one-sentence body), a "what to watch" event pointer, and
a signal color. Currently implemented as a direct Anthropic API call from
the frontend — must be proxied through the backend.

Add endpoint:
  POST /api/signal-briefing
    Body: {signal_id, signal_name, category, probability, prev_probability}
    Returns: {trend_pts:[7 numbers oldest-to-newest ending near current
             value], drivers:[{title, body} x3], watch:{event, detail},
             color:"#hex"}

Caching strategy: cache results for 6 hours keyed on signal_id. Same
signal re-opened within that window serves from cache. Invalidate cache
when the underlying probability moves more than 3 percentage points.

Store in a new table:
  signal_briefings
    signal_id       — market or signal ID
    payload         — JSON of the full briefing
    prob_at_compute — probability at time of compute (for invalidation)
    computed_at     — timestamp

Cost estimate: ~$0.003-$0.005 per briefing; with 6-hour caching assume
~200-400 generations/day at peak → $0.60-$2.00/day.


9. VIX DRIVER EXPLAINER
The VIX card on the dashboard displays a short "what's driving the VIX
today" explainer — a 2-3 sentence description of the single most important
event/data release/market development moving the VIX, plus an up/down/flat
direction indicator and an approximate change value. Currently a direct
Anthropic API call — must be proxied through the backend.

Add endpoint:
  GET /api/vix-driver
    Returns: {driver:"event name (5 words max)", detail:"2-3 sentence
             explanation", direction:"up|down|flat", change:"e.g. +2.1 pts",
             vix_value, computed_at}

Refresh strategy: regenerate once every 30 minutes during US market hours
(9:30am-4:00pm ET, Mon-Fri) and once at 9am and 5pm ET on non-market days.
Cache the most recent result and serve it to all users from cache. No
per-user API calls.

Store in a new table (or reuse fred_data metadata):
  vix_driver
    id              — singleton row (always "latest")
    payload         — JSON of the full driver object
    vix_at_compute  — VIX value at time of compute
    computed_at     — timestamp

Cost estimate: ~48 generations/day → under $0.25/day.


STATIC FRONTEND CONTENT — NO BACKEND NEEDED:
The Frontline Insights panel contains a WEF Global Risk Landscape chart
card (a clickable thumbnail that opens a full-screen SVG lightbox showing
all 33 risks from the World Economic Forum Global Risks Report 2026,
Figure 2). This is static SVG built into index.html — no API calls, no
data fetching, no backend involvement. If future WEF data updates are
needed, the SVG bar values and labels are edited directly in the HTML.
The lightbox is a self-contained overlay with its own open/close JS
functions (openWEFChart / closeWEFChart) and an ESC-to-close keybinding.

The Frontline Insights panel also contains a RAND Report card titled
"RAND Report: Perceptions of Possible Global Threats and Hazards"
(placed between the MIT Sloan link and the WEF chart). The card has
the report title, source citation, brief summary, topic tags, an
external link to the source URL
(https://www.rand.org/pubs/research_reports/RRA4329-1.html), and two
clickable thumbnail charts. Figure 1 shows percentage of U.S. adults
very or somewhat concerned about six global threats (stacked bars);
Figure 2 shows percentage who believe each risk is increasing (single
bars). Both thumbnails open into a shared lightbox overlay
(openRandFigure / closeRandFigure) with a tab switcher at the bottom
to toggle between Figure 1 and Figure 2 without closing. Both figures
are recreated as native SVG using data from the RAND American Life
Panel survey (May-June 2025, n=8,793) - RAND's PNG charts are NOT
embedded directly. The data values, labels, and styling are baked
into _randFigure1HTML() and _randFigure2HTML() and can be edited
directly. ESC/backdrop/x closes the lightbox.

The Frontline Insights panel header is also clickable and expands an
inline Interactive Risk Ranker — an 85-topic horizontal bar chart
rendered as a single SVG that visually mirrors the WEF Global Risks
Report Figure 2 chart exactly (same coordinate system, same fonts,
same row spacing, same Figure-style header bar, same x-axis tick marks
and axis title, same source caption + risk-category legend at the
bottom). Topics are grouped into 10 collapsible category sections —
Geopolitics, US Politics, Financial Markets, Technology, Cybersecurity,
Legal & Regulatory, Safety & Security, Global Health & Medical,
Society, and Environment. Each section header shows the category name
with its color accent, an expand/collapse arrow, and a "X / Y scored"
counter. All sections start collapsed so users opt into what to score;
"Expand all" and "Collapse all" buttons in the toolbar provide bulk
control. Switching to "By score" view flattens everything into a
single ranked list (no grouping, leaderboard mode).

The chart starts empty (no bars drawn) and bars grow as the user
clicks. Each row's bar lane is divided into 5 invisible SVG click-zone
rectangles — clicking the 1st zone fills the bar 20% (score 1), the
5th zone fills it 100% (score 5). Clicking the same zone twice clears
the score. Bars are colored by the risk's RANE category using the
canonical CATS palette. The score value (1, 2, 3, 4, or 5) appears as
a bold text label at the bar's tip, in the same visual style WEF uses
for percentages.

The chart has an expand button (⤢) that opens the same chart in a
full-screen lightbox overlay (mirroring the WEF lightbox treatment,
with ESC/backdrop/✕ to close), a counter showing how many risks have
been scored and how many are rated 4-5 ("high priority"), a Reset
button, and an "Export to Survey" button. The inline panel view and
the lightbox view stay in sync — scoring in one updates both. Scores
persist via localStorage under the key "wef_risk_ranking_v3" and need
no backend storage. When the user exports, all risks rated 4 or 5 are
auto-added to the Enterprise Pulse Survey custom builder as
pre-checked topics in their respective categories — the survey name
is preset to "My Top-Ranked Risks" and the user proceeds through the
normal Pulse Survey generation flow from there.

The 85-topic list and topic-to-category mapping live in the
RANKER_TOPICS constant, the category render order in RANKER_CAT_ORDER,
and category colors in the canonical CATS array — all in index.html
and editable directly. The CATS array now has two new entries beyond
the 8 that drive the rest of the index: "society" (slate teal,
#1F6B7A) and "environment" (olive/moss, #5C7A1F). These are used by
the Risk Ranker only; they do not yet have signals/markets feeding
them in other parts of the index. The SVG layout constants (ROW_STEP,
SECTION_GAP, HEADER_H, FIRST_Y, BAR_H, BAR_X0, BAR_W_FULL, BAR_W_PER)
are defined inline in _renderRankerInto() and can be tuned per-mode
(inline vs lightbox) without breaking the click logic.


IMPORTANT — SECURING THE ANTHROPIC API KEY:
The current index.html file calls api.anthropic.com directly from the
browser for feeds 6, 7, 8, and 9. This exposes the Anthropic API key
client-side. Before going live, all four Anthropic-powered features must
be refactored so the frontend calls the backend endpoints listed above
instead of api.anthropic.com directly. The backend holds the Anthropic
key in the .env file and is the only party that talks to Anthropic.

Find and replace all four direct-fetch blocks in index.html:
  - _spFetchConsensus               → GET /api/consensus/:id
  - side-panel briefing generator   → POST /api/signal-briefing
  - VIX driver generator            → GET /api/vix-driver
  - Enterprise Pulse Survey (both   → POST /api/pulse/generate-single
    single-topic and custom flows)    POST /api/pulse/generate-custom


DATABASE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Use PostgreSQL via Supabase for storage. Create tables for:
  markets            — current prices from all platforms
  market_history     — price logs (every fetch logged to build historical record)
  news_items         — RSS entries with category tags and sentiment scores
  gjopen_questions   — forecasts and probability history
  fred_data          — economic series values including VIX intraday and daily
  ai_consensus       — pre-computed AI Platforms Consensus for all markets
  signal_briefings   — cached side-panel briefings (6-hour TTL, probability-
                       move invalidation)
  vix_driver         — singleton cache of the latest VIX driver explainer
  pulse_surveys      — (Phase 2, optional at launch) sent surveys, question
                       payloads, delivery settings, response aggregates

Log every price fetch to market_history from day one so trend sparkline charts
self-build over time. After ~2 weeks of logging, full 14-day trend lines will
be available. After 6 months, full sparkline range is available.


API ENDPOINTS:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Serve the following endpoints to the HTML file:

  GET /api/markets
  All current market prices from Polymarket and Kalshi, normalized to this
  exact format: {id, cat, name, platform, prob, vol, prev}
  prob must be a number 0-100 representing percentage.
  cat must use these exact IDs: geo, uspol, fin, tech, cyber, legal, safety,
  medical.

  GET /api/market/:id/history
  Price history array for a specific market ID, used to populate sparkline
  trend charts in the side panel.

  GET /api/nm-signals
  Non-monied signals including GJOpen forecasts, normalized for the
  Non-Monied section of the dashboard.

  GET /api/news/breaking
  Latest breaking news items from the past 2 hours, filtered by active
  category tab selection.

  GET /api/news/research
  Research institution and polling RSS entries for the Intelligence Reports
  and Polling & Research sections.

  GET /api/fred
  Current values for all FRED series plus VIX intraday status:
  {vix:{value, source, market_open, updated_at}, sp500, dgs10, fedfunds,
  cpi, unrate, gdp, recession_prob}

  GET /api/consensus/:id
  Pre-computed AI Platforms Consensus for a given market or signal ID.
  Returns: {market_id, claude_pct, deepseek_pct, gemini_pct, gpt4_pct,
  grok_pct, mistral_pct, perplexity_pct, avg_pct, spread, consensus_note,
  computed_at}
  Falls back to live Claude API call if no cached result exists.

  POST /api/signal-briefing
  Generate or return cached side-panel briefing for a clicked signal.
  Body: {signal_id, signal_name, category, probability, prev_probability}
  Returns: {trend_pts, drivers, watch, color}
  Cached 6 hours, invalidated on >3pp probability moves.

  GET /api/vix-driver
  Latest cached VIX driver explainer.
  Returns: {driver, detail, direction, change, vix_value, computed_at}
  Refreshed every 30 minutes during US market hours, twice daily
  otherwise.

  POST /api/pulse/generate-single
  Generate Enterprise Pulse Survey questions for a single signal.
  Body: {signal_name, category, probability, industry_label}
  Returns: {questions:[{num, text, type, low?, high?, placeholder?}],
  industry_context}

  POST /api/pulse/generate-custom
  Generate Enterprise Pulse Survey questions across multiple topics.
  Body: {survey_name, topics:[{sig, cat}], sector}
  Returns: {survey_title, questions:[{num, text, type, low?, high?,
  placeholder?, topic}], summary}


DEPLOYMENT:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Set up the full project in this folder with this structure:
     frontend/
       index.html
     backend/
       server.js
       package.json
       .env
       feeds/
         polymarket.js
         kalshi.js
         fred.js
         vix.js
         gjopen.js
         rss.js
       jobs/
         scheduler.js
         dedup.js
         consensus.js
         vix-driver.js
       ai/
         pulse-survey.js
         signal-briefing.js
         anthropic-client.js
       db/
         schema.sql
         queries.js
     .gitignore
     README.md

2. Initialize a Git repository in the root folder.

3. Create a .env file for all API keys. Never commit this file to GitHub.
   Required keys at launch:
     KALSHI_API_KEY
     FRED_API_KEY
     ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
     SUPABASE_URL
     SUPABASE_DB_STRING
     PORT (default 3000)
   Optional keys for Phase 3 AI upgrades:
     OPENAI_API_KEY
     GOOGLE_AI_KEY
     MISTRAL_API_KEY
     DEEPSEEK_API_KEY
     PERPLEXITY_API_KEY

4. Create a .gitignore file that excludes: .env, node_modules, and any
   other sensitive or unnecessary files.

5. Push everything (except .env) to my GitHub repository called:
   risk-intelligence-index

6. Create a railway.json configuration file so the backend can be deployed
   to Railway with one click after connecting the GitHub repository.

7. Create a netlify.toml configuration file so the frontend folder deploys
   automatically from GitHub to Netlify.

8. Update the PROXY_BASE_URL variable in index.html to be configurable via
   an environment variable so it automatically points to the correct backend
   URL in production versus local development.


IMPORTANT NOTES:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Read index.html fully before writing any code. The data formats, category
  IDs, and field names in the backend must match exactly what the HTML
  already expects.

- The HTML file uses these exact category IDs throughout:
  geo, uspol, fin, tech, cyber, legal, safety, medical
  All backend data must use these same IDs without exception.

- Market probability must always be a number 0-100 representing percentage.

- SECURITY — THE ANTHROPIC API KEY MUST NEVER REACH THE BROWSER.
  The current index.html calls api.anthropic.com directly from four
  places: AI Platforms Consensus, Side-Panel Signal Briefings, VIX
  Driver Explainer, and Enterprise Pulse Survey (both single-topic and
  custom flows). Before deployment, refactor every one of these so the
  frontend calls your backend endpoints instead. The backend holds the
  Anthropic key in .env and is the only party that talks to Anthropic.

- When you need API keys from me, ask for them one at a time and wait for
  my response before continuing.

- After completing each major section, tell me what was built and what the
  next step is.

- When everything is ready to push to GitHub, tell me first and confirm
  before pushing.

- Please start by reading index.html, then tell me your plan before writing
  any code.


